HEADWORD: Gruff
<hw>Gruff</hw> <pr>(gr⟦ucr⟧f)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Gruffer</adjf>
<pr>(gr⟦ucr⟧f"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Gruffest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[D. <ets>grof</ets>; akin to G.
<ets>grob</ets>, OHG. <ets>gerob</ets>, grob, Dan. <ets>grov</ets>, Sw.
<ets>grof</ets>, perh. akin to AS. <ets>rc⟦oacute⟧fan</ets> to break, Z.
<ets>reavc</ets>, rupture, <ets>g-</ets> standing for the AS. prefix
<ets>ge-</ets>, Goth. <ets>ga-</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of a rough or stern
manner, voice, or countenance; sour; surly; severe; harsh.</def>
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Gruff</qex>, disagreeable, sarcastic remarks.</q>
<rj><qau>Thackeray.</qau></rj></p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Gruff"ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Gruff"ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

